Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Instance 1: Constructs Involved: Register Team, Validate Team Roster, include relationship from Register Team to Validate Team Roster
   Instance 1: Explanation: "Validate Team Roster" is an inclusion use case included only by "Register Team." It is not associated with any actor, is not included by any other use case, does not include or extend any use case, is not extended by any use case, and has no generalization relationships. It represents an internal validation step (checking roster size, player eligibility) rather than a complete, independently valuable service. This is functional decomposition — breaking "Register Team" into a sub-step that provides no observable result to any actor on its own.

   Instance 2: Constructs Involved: Schedule Match, Assign Server Instance, include relationship from Schedule Match to Assign Server Instance
   Instance 2: Explanation: "Assign Server Instance" is an inclusion use case included only by "Schedule Match." It is not associated with any actor, is not included by any other use case, does not include or extend any use case, is not extended by any use case, and has no generalization relationships. Assigning a game server is an internal infrastructure step within scheduling a match, not a standalone service observable to any user. This decomposes "Schedule Match" into a sub-function unnecessarily.

   Instance 3: Constructs Involved: Process Prize Payout, Calculate Prize Split, include relationship from Process Prize Payout to Calculate Prize Split
   Instance 3: Explanation: "Calculate Prize Split" is an inclusion use case included only by "Process Prize Payout." It is not associated with any actor, is not included by any other use case, does not include or extend any use case, is not extended by any use case, and has no generalization relationships. Calculating how prize money is split among team members is an internal computational step within processing a payout, not a complete service offered to any actor. This is a classic functional decomposition of "Process Prize Payout."
